# .dockerignore - trims the Docker build context for the root Dockerfile.
#
# The Dockerfile's build context is the repository ROOT so that MSBuild can
# resolve the demo's transitive project/props references (Algo, BusinessEntities,
# Messages, the common_*.props files, the Database/ SQL init scripts, etc.).
# Everything listed below is a NON-build artifact that is safe to keep out of the
# context: it makes `docker build` / `docker compose build` faster and smaller and
# prevents stale local output from leaking into the image.
#
# IMPORTANT: never add patterns here that would exclude source needed by the
# build: *.csproj, *.props, *.cs, *.sql, or the source project folders. Doing so
# would break the transitive restore/publish inside the container.
#
# Syntax: one pattern per line; lines beginning with '#' are comments. '**'
# matches nested directories at any depth (Docker normalizes trailing slashes).

# --- Build output (regenerated by the build; safe and recommended to drop) ---
**/bin/
**/obj/

# --- Version control metadata (not needed to build the app) ---
.git/
.gitignore
.gitattributes

# --- IDE / editor state ---
.vs/
.vscode/
*.user

# --- QA evidence (screenshots/recordings; large and not needed to build) ---
QA/

# --- Container/compose definitions (not needed inside the image itself) ---
Dockerfile
.dockerignore
docker-compose.yml
